A group of two membra which Augustine characterizes as “ardens'’.

“The majestic style of speech differs from the Temperate Style ...... chiefly in that it is not so much decked out with verbal ornaments as exalted into vehemence by mental emotion. It useS, indeed, nearly all the ornaments that the other does; but if they do not happen to be at hand it does not seek for them. For it is borne on by its own vehemence; and the force of the thought, not the desire for ornament, makes it seize upon any beauty of expres- sion that comes in its way.'' (D. D. C. IV, 20. 42).
